Title: Object: John Bull on the Watch or Old England for Ever
Description: Political satire: John Bull on a patch of land in the sea labelled "England", fires at Napoleon, fleeing froglike on hands and knees across other patches of land labelled "Ireland", "Holland", "Switzerland" and "Italy", saying "I thought it would be Veni, vidi, vici - I'm off!"; pyramids marked "Egypt" are visible in the distance. June 1803 Hand-coloured etching
Bibliographic references: BM Satires / Catalogue of Political and Personal Satires in the Department of Prints and Drawings in the British Museum (undescribed)
Associated names: Representation of: Napoléon I, Emperor of the French (Napoleon)
